III. APPLICABLE LEGAL FRAMEWORK
INA § 203(b)(1)(A) provides immigrant classification to an individual who:
1. Has extraordinary ability in the sciences, arts, education, business, or athletics;
2. Has sustained national or international acclaim;
3. Has achievements recognized in the field through extensive documentation;
4. Seeks to enter or remain in the United States to continue working in the area of extraordinary ability; and
5. Will prospectively substantially benefit the United States.

Under 8 C.F.R. § 204.5(h), extraordinary ability refers to a level of expertise indicating that the individual is among the small percentage who have risen to the very top of the field of endeavor.

Eligibility may be demonstrated through evidence of either:
1. A one-time achievement consisting of a major, internationally recognized award; or
2. At least three of the evidentiary criteria listed at 8 C.F.R. § 204.5(h)(3).

Where the regulatory criteria do not readily apply to the Petitioner's occupation, comparable evidence may be submitted under 8 C.F.R. § 204.5(h)(4).

The adjudication involves two analytically distinct steps:
1. Determining whether the submitted evidence objectively satisfies the claimed regulatory criteria; and
2. Evaluating the evidence in its totality to determine whether the Petitioner has sustained national or international acclaim and is among the small percentage who have risen to the very top of the field.

The evidence submitted with this petition satisfies both steps.

